english:
  title: Drinking at the Bamboo Pavilion with Friends
  author: Lim Yujung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Who planted these sparse bamboo that have already grown into a grove?
    A cool breeze from all four sides drifts across the railings.
    The moon sends its green shadows slanting up the stone steps.
    Among the rocks, crimson autumn leaves adorn themselves with grace.
    I urge you—let us share another cup of wine,
    And together forget the sorrows of ten thousand ages.
    Drunk, I lie upon white clouds, wandering idly into dreams,
    Where a solitary butterfly dances, fluttering gently on my pillow.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is a creative collage composed of poetic allusions and couplets attributed to famous Chinese poets (Li Bangzhi, Cai Zhizheng, Fang Gan, Shun Qin, Wang Wei, Li Bai, Su Guangwen, and Song Bai), masterfully woven together by the author to capture a moment of convivial drinking and reverie in a bamboo pavilion.
